1. Staff Management
• 	The system must allow registration of employees (name, position, schedule, shift).
• 	It must support assigning shifts and schedules by day.
• 	The manager must be able to view staff attendance and performance.


2. Table Management
• 	The system must display the status of each table (free, occupied, reserved).
• 	It must allow reservations to be made by customers or the manager.
• 	Waiters must be able to link orders to specific tables.


3. Order Management
• 	Waiters must be able to record customer orders in the system.
• 	The kitchen must receive orders in real time.
• 	The system must update the order status (in preparation, ready, delivered).
• 	It must store the history of orders for later analysis.


4. Inventory Management
• 	The system must track the stock of goods (food, drinks, materials).
• 	It must alert when a product is running low.
• 	The owner or manager must be able to add or update items in the inventory.


5. Customer Management
• 	The system must store basic customer data (name, contact, preferences).
• 	It must allow reservations online or through staff.
• 	It must keep a history of orders for each customer.


6. Reporting and Analytics
• 	The system must generate daily, weekly, and monthly sales reports.
• 	It must analyze the most requested products and staff performance.
• 	The owner must have access to financial and statistical reports.


7. Security and Access Control
• 	The system must provide authentication with username and password.
• 	Each role (Owner, Manager, Waiter, Kitchen) must have restricted access according to their function.
• 	Data must be stored securely and not accessible to unauthorized users.
